Explanation:

- *Gibbs*: $(partial G / partial P)_T = V$, so $(partial^2 G / partial P^2)_T = (partial V / partial P)_T$.
- *Helmholtz*: $(partial F / partial V)_T = -P$, so $(partial^2 F / partial V^2)_T = -(partial P / partial V)_T$.
- *Relation*: Use the identity $(partial V / partial P)_T = 1 / (partial P / partial V)_T$ to relate the two results.
